    <annotation>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Hercules playeth the braue man, where he becummes: and for more reputation of his unmatchable valour, reporteth himself the Son of the mightie God.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Hercules"/>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>I. Romuli historia regia.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Romulus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>I. The royal history of Romulus.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>strategemata Caci. qualia nonnulla Sisyphi memorantur. vt erant veteres Heroes abigei.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Cacus"/>
                    <person name="Sisyphys"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The strategems of Cacus, of the kind that remind of some of Sisyphus' tricks. As the old heroes were cattle-thieves.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Neotechnia, instar Thaumaturgiae. Huc totus Polydorus de Inventoribus rerum.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Polydore Vergil"/>
                    <book title="De Inventoribus Rerum"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Innovative skills, equal to miracle working. On this subject see the entire Polydore Virgil, De inventoribus rerum.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Pore Euander glad to flatter, &amp; deifie Hercules. His honorable interteinment of Aeneas in Virgil. A politique prince, &amp; discreet old man. The son of Carmenta, a cunning wooman.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Virgil"/>
                    <person name="Aeneas"/>
                    <person name="Carmenta"/>
                </position>
            </language>
         </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Euschemosyne regia. Prisca magnificentia, ad augustiorem decorem, ab heroicis vsq[ue] temporibus vsurpata.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Royal decorum. Ancient majesty for a more dignified elegance, employed all the way from heroic times.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Senatores, Regis, creatura[e]: ad consilium: non ad vires, aut cohibitionem, aut tale quid.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Senators are the king's clients: they are there for counsel, not force, or governing, or anything of that kind.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Prima omnium, Jura. Tum insignia imperij: lictores xii. Munitiones: asylum: Senatores centum: Legati ad vicinas gentes: Nulla peregrina Sacra, pra[e]ter Herculea; apta robusto S.P.Q.R.
                        Asyli ratio, ecc&egrave; apud Augustinum, l. I. c. 34. de Civit. De clementia Dei, qua[e] vrbis excidiu[m] temperavit. Quod magnum, si hoc feceru[n]t vrbis conditores, vt civium suoru[m] numerus suppleretur; quod fecerunt eversores, vt suorum hostium numerositas servaretur?
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Augustine"/>
                    <person name="De Civitate Dei"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>First of all there were legal provisions. Then came the signs of authority: the twelve lictors; fortifications; asylum; the hundred senators; the ambassadors to neighbouring clans; there were no foreign rituals, except the Herculean ones, which were suitable for a strong Roman government. 
                For the principle of asylum, see Augustine, City of God, bk. 1, c. 34: On the mercy of God in tempering the Cityâ€™s destruction. But how can it be a great thing, if the founders of the City did this to increase the number of their own citizens, whereas the overthrowers did it to spare the multitude of their enemies?</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
